    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tips on drainage. but i was thinking maybe it's a nutrient thing? i read somewhere that yellowing on the old leaves specifically means they are missing something from the soil. could it be nitrogen? if so how do i check if my soil ph is actually the problem?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the yellowing is confined to the older leaves, it might indeed be a nutrient deficiency, with nitrogen being a common culprit. To check if your soil pH is the problem, you'll need a soil pH test kit. These kits are readily available at garden centers or online. Follow the instructions on the kit to collect a soil sample from the affected area and then test the pH level. The ideal pH for tomato plants is between 6.0 and 6.8. If your soil pH is outside this range, you might need to adjust it using lime to raise the pH or sulfur to lower it. Remember, it's important to test the soil several inches below the surface, as the top layer where you plant your tomatoes might not represent the overall pH of your garden bed. Once you have the pH results, you can take the appropriate steps to correct any imbalances. Keep in mind that adjusting soil pH is a gradual process, so be patient and retest after a few months to see if there has been an improvement. Happy gardening, and may your tomatoes flourish with the right nutrients and soil conditions!",
      "source": "target",
